<br>
Historically, Lutherans practice what is called close communion. While most people think of that in a negative, exclusive concept (and it is exclusive, but so is the Gospel), there is a far more important positive feature. Because Lutherans believe that receiving the Lord's Supper is a public confession of the faith, we desire that someone who receives at the Lord's Table understands, accepts, and wishes to publicly identify with the public teachings of what it means to be Christian and Lutheran by confession. So, we have historically provided instruction in the chief teachings of Christian doctrine (God/Trinity - as expressed in the Apostles' Creed, Law/Gospel dialect, Law, Baptism. Lord's Supper, Confession/Absolution, and Prayer). The LCMS, of which Jebleez and I are part, practices close communion. But with the understanding that the pastor has discretion in administering that; in other words, I have on occasion allowed a non-Lutheran to receive the Lord's Supper.<br>
<br>
Some Lutheran denominations have abandoned that approach, namely the ELCA (Evangelical Lutheran Church in America). They practice semi-open communion. That is, they allow anyone who claims to be a Christian to the altar, but not &quot;anyone&quot; nor do they give the elements to infants (something the Orthodox Church does).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What is the Lutheran belief about the Lord's Supper- that it is symbolic of receiving Jesus Christ, or a sacrament that is actually receiving the Body of Christ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There are three fundamentally different beliefs regarding the Lord's Supper:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1. Roman Catholic/Orthodox</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (some differences, but for this purpose they are similar).<br>
<br>
Real presence of the body and blood of Jesus Christ.<br>
<br>
Transubstantiation: bread changed into body of Christ; wine changed into blood of Christ - bread and wine no longer are present.<br>
<br>
For the forgiveness of sins, but it is an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>act</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> which merits extra grace. (Typical phrase, historically was &quot;I make communion&quot;)<br>
<br>
Priest re-sacrifices Christ every time he celebrates the Mass<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2. General Protestant/Reformed</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Real presence of Christ,&quot; but not the real presence of the body and blood of Christ. The presence of Christ is the same as his presence with Christians everywhere.<br>
<br>
An ordinance that the Christian must follow. Since bread and wine are only symbols (body and blood of Christ are not present), any convenient food can be used.<br>
<br>
External/horizontal relationship is crucial. The effect of the Lord’s Supper is for believers only.<br>
<br>
Basically open communion although some Presbyterian groups do practice close communion. Anyone who wants to receive may do so. Fellowship is “being together” (horizontal relationship) and most important. “What I believe is important. What others believe is their business.”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3. Lutheran</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Real presence of the body and blood of Jesus Christ (“in, with, and under” the elements).<br>
<br>
Body of Christ is present in, with, and under the bread. Blood of Christ is present in, with, and under the wine. Note how Paul addresses this:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1 Cor. 10:16<br>
Is not the cup of blessing which we bless a sharing (participation - KOINONIA) in the blood of Christ? Is not the bread which we break a sharing (participation - KOINONIA) in the body of Christ? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For the forgiveness of sins and the strengthening of the faith of those who receive the benefits through faith. Unbelievers also receive the body and blood of Christ, but to their damnation.<br>
<br>
Fellowship at the Lord’s Table means a common confession of the faith. Vertical and horizontal dimensions are both important. What the church publicly teaches and what I believe are equally important.<br>
<br>
===========<br>
<br>
Obviously, those who Roman Catholic/Orthodox/Reformed can present their beliefs more fully, but this at least lays out the issues and differences. <p>In Christ,<br>
<br>
filo<br>
<br>
For I decided to know nothing among you except Jesus Christ and him crucified.<br>
