<br>
Re: Transubstantiation.  Catholics believe (and probably Orthodox) that the bread becomes the Body and Blood, Soul &amp; Divinity of our Lord.  Same with the wine.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Priest re-sacrifices Christ every time he celebrates the Mass<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      We DO NOT believe that!!  We believe that there was ONE sacrifice and the priest re - presents it to our Father.<br>
<br>
<br>
We also agree with: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For the forgiveness of sins and the strengthening of the faith of those who receive the benefits through faith. Unbelievers also receive the body and blood of Christ, but to their damnation.<br>
<br>
Fellowship at the Lord’s Table means a common confession of the faith. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p>“How can you claim to love a God you can’t see if you fail to love the brother or sister standing right in front of you?” – Mother Theresa</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 666<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/3/03 9:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=24>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Malachi 1</span><hr size=1> Just a quick chime in on the Catholic stuff.<br>
<br>
In regards to the sacrifice thing - while I lean towards what <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Tommy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> mentioned, I'm not sure that is absolutely correct.  I've been trying to read up on what the &quot;Sacrifice of the Mass&quot; actually means, and I have seen an extreme variation of opinions - even from Catholic writers.  Hopefully, if I get accepted into the Catholic college I applied to for May, I can learn what is the actual view.<br>
<br>
On the transubstantiation issue, the whole of the bread and wine is not changed but only the substance.  It apparaently goes back to Socratic (or Aristotelian - I can't remember which one) thought that all matter is composed of a substance (its true reality) and its accident (the form we perceive with our mortal senses).  In transubstantiation, the substance becomes the flesh and blood yet the accidents remain as bread and wine.<br>
<br>
I also remember <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Jeff</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> making the comment that the Orthodox do believe in a transformation as well, however, they do not use the term transubstantiation or consubstantiation.  It simply happens and is a Holy mystery.<br>
<br>
Sometimes, I like that answer the best!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
