<br>
I think the biggest difference regarding what happens in the Lord's Supper is that the RCC teaches (as noted above) that this is a sacrifice (hence, Law = something the person does), because the grace makes the person worthy to be forgiven, whereas Lutherans would say that it is sacrament meaning that the person is forgiven not because of being worthy, but because of what Christ has done for the person (Gospel = something that God does). <br>
<br>
Obviously we can see that there are definition problems, partly because Lutherans and RCC define &quot;sacrament&quot; differently. (BTW, I would partially agree with the Orthodox statement about  &quot;it's a mystery&quot; since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>sacramentum</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in Latin means &quot;mystery.&quot;) For Lutherans, we define a sacrament as having three parts:<br>
<br>
1. Instituted by Christ<br>
<br>
2. For the forgiveness of sins<br>
<br>
3. Visible element(s)<br>
<br>
According to this definition, only Baptism (Matthew 28:18-20;  Acts 2:38-39; 1 Peter 3:21; Romans 6:1-5) and the Lord's Supper (Matthew 26:26-28 and parallels; 1 Corinthians 10:16-17 and 11:23-30) would be considered sacraments (means of grace). (Sometimes you might hear/read about the &quot;1/2 sacrament&quot; - namely, Confession/Absolution, but it lacks the visible sign.<br>
<br>
RCC doctrine provides a different definition, and thus ends up with seven sacraments: Baptism, Confirmation, Lord's Supper, marriage, holy orders, penance, extreme unction/last rites. <p>In Christ,<br>
<br>
filo<br>
<br>
For I decided to know nothing among you except Jesus Christ and him crucified.<br>
<br>
1 Corinthians 2:2</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:maroon;><b>Administrator<br>Sir Esdras,<br>Master, Knights of the Realm,<br>Peacekeeper Extraordinaire,<br>Canadian, eh.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 671<br> <font color=#B87333>(12/4/03 9:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=30>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: sacrifice</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I think the biggest difference regarding what happens in the Lord's Supper is that the RCC teaches (as noted above) that this is a sacrifice (hence, Law = something the person does), because the grace makes the person worthy to be forgiven, whereas Lutherans would say that it is sacrament meaning that the person is forgiven not because of being worthy, but because of what Christ has done for the person (Gospel = something that God does).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think that even though the priest during the Mass goes through the actions of the sacrifice - the grace is still all from God.<br>
<br>
Additionally, what we offer (or sacrifice) at the Mass is the bread and the wine (fruit of the vine and work of human hands).  Additionally, when we say what we have to offer, we begin with, &quot;Blessed are you, Lord, God of all creation. Through your goodness we have this (bread/wine) to offer.  Even our offering is becuase of God.<br>
<br>
Ultimately, the bread and wine becomes the body and blood through the power of the Holy Spirit, as the priest says, &quot;Lord, you are holy indeed, the fountain of all holiness. Let your Spirit come upon these gifts to make them holy, so that they may become for us the body and blood of our Lord, Jesus Christ.&quot;<br>
<br>
We also reaffirm that we are not worthy to receive the body and blood or be forgiven.  Before receiving communion the congregation says what is, in my opinion, one of the most important statements uttered by the participants of a Mass...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Lord, I am not worthy to receive you, but only say the word and I shall be healed.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
That is said just before we go to receive communion.<br>
<br>
So while there is an offering/sacrifice presented during the Mass, I never really see that as the focal point.  That one line I quoted above and then receiving the body and blood is the most glorious part of the Mass.  And at that time, the focus is not on ourselves, but on God, Jesus Christ and the grace and sacrifice given to us, even though not one of us is worthy to receive the gift.<br>
<br>
 <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
